Study 1 Scope and Related Results

Overall scores are moderately correlated between tests.

We found that individual participant scores on GGR were moderately predictive of their score on VLAT. Moreover, participants generally did best on Level 1 (“read the data”) and successively less well on Level 2 (“read between the data”) and Level 3 (“read beyond the data”) questions, consistent with a “three-level hierarchy.” However, we did not find evidence for a similar hierarchy among VLAT questions.

Inter-item reliability is weak within question type.

Inter-item reliability is weak within question type. Insofar as each question type (e.g., “read beyond the data”) corresponds to a psychologically coherent construct, we predicted that success on these items would be reliable within a participant. However, we instead found that many question types achieved low reliability, including ones that one might have thought to be more straightforward to define (e.g., “retrieve value”).

Scores on specific types of questions were correlated within-test, but weakly between tests.

Scores on specific types of questions were correlated within-test, but weakly between tests. Even questions that you might think were designed to get at the same thing aren’t predictive of each other (i.e., “read the data” in GGR and “retrieve value” in VLAT).

Generalizability - Relative performance is remarkably consistent.

Insofar as these assessments have high generalizability and measure graph comprehension, overall performance on these assessments and their respective decomposition structures should be replicated between samples. Performance from the university sample (recruited from the SONA platform) at the task-level, graph-level, and item-level should predict performance from the broder, US-demographically (recruited from the Prolific platform) represented sample.
